1.1 Dilemmas of the Traditional Interpretation
For more than three hundred years since Newton discovered the ring pattern, wave optics has attributed Newton’s rings to optical interference generated by two reflected wave components on the upper and lower surfaces of the air thin film. Although mathematically concise, this explanation leaves fundamental physical contradictions unsolved: why does destructive interference produce an absolute zero light intensity? Why do interference patterns exhibit rigid topological stability? And how can wave-particle duality be logically unified within this system?
